# Task Prioritizer - Environment Variables Template
# Copy this file to .env and fill in your actual credentials

# Gemini AI Configuration (Feature 002)
# Get your API key from: https://makersuite.google.com/app/apikey
VITE_GEMINI_API_KEY=your_gemini_api_key_here

# Supabase Configuration (Feature 003)
# Get these from your Supabase project dashboard: Settings → API
# 1. Project URL: Your unique Supabase project URL
VITE_SUPABASE_URL=https://your-project-ref.supabase.co

# 2. Anonymous (anon) key: Public API key for client-side access
# This is a long JWT token starting with "eyJ..."
VITE_SUPABASE_ANON_KEY=your_supabase_anon_key_here

# ==============================================================================
# SETUP INSTRUCTIONS
# ==============================================================================
#
# For Gemini AI (if not already configured):
# 1. Visit https://makersuite.google.com/app/apikey
# 2. Sign in with your Google account
# 3. Click "Create API key"
# 4. Copy the key and paste it above
#
# For Supabase Database Logging:
# 1. Create a free account at https://supabase.com
# 2. Create a new project (takes ~2 minutes)
# 3. Go to Settings → API in your project
# 4. Copy "Project URL" and paste it above
# 5. Copy "anon public" key and paste it above
# 6. Run the database schema SQL (see specs/003-supabase-logging/quickstart.md)
# 7. Configure RLS policies (see quickstart.md Step 4)
# 8. Restart your dev server: npm run dev
#
# ==============================================================================
# SECURITY NOTES
# ==============================================================================
#
# ⚠️ NEVER commit the .env file to version control
# ✅ The .env file is already in .gitignore
# ✅ Share this .env.example file (without real credentials) with your team
# ✅ For production deployments, use platform environment variables
#
# Supabase Free Tier Limits (sufficient for workshops):
# - 50,000 database rows
# - 500 MB storage
# - 2 GB bandwidth per month
# - Unlimited API requests
#
# Workshop Context:
# The anonymous (anon) key is intentionally exposed to the browser for this
# demo. Row Level Security (RLS) policies protect your data. This pattern is
# acceptable for workshops but production apps should use a backend API proxy.
#
